<br>
Although this thing can produce fusion of D-3He and DD, it is far from producing net electric power.  The factor Q tells you your power output.<br>
<br>
Q &lt; 1 - Net power loss<br>
Q = 1 - Physics power breakeven<br>
Q &gt; 10 - Engineering breakeven/net electricity production<br>
Q = infinity - uncontrolled burning fusion (H-bomb/stars)<br>
<br>
Current IEC designs have a Q of around 10^-8 so you have a very, very long way to go.  ITER will have a Q = 10, so technically it will be a power producing reactor of about 100 MWe if you hooked it up to a turbine and breeding blanket.  So IEC may work, but there really needs to be a lot more work on it.  At this point, IEC is a huge unknown.  MFE and IFE have their own issues as well, but they seem a lot more promising than IEC at this point.<br>
<br>
